  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A mortgagee in possession sale is what happens when a borrower defaults on their mortgage and the lender, called the mortgagee, takes legal possession of the property and sells it to recover the outstanding debt. It is sometimes called a forced sale or a bank sale. For the borrower, it represents a significant loss of control over one of their most valuable assets, and understanding what is happening legally and practically can still make a real difference to the outcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When can a lender exercise the power of sale in Queensland?</h2>
      <p>Under the Property Law Act 1974 (Qld), the power of sale arises once the mortgage is in default. For a registered mortgage, this typically means the lender has issued a formal demand for repayment and the borrower has failed to remedy the default within the required period, which is usually 30 days from the date of service. The specific terms of your mortgage document will govern the exact trigger conditions, so it is important to read that document carefully and seek legal advice as soon as a default notice arrives.</p>

      <p>It is worth noting that a default notice does not mean the lender will immediately sell. Most lenders view forced sales as a last resort because they are expensive, time-consuming, and frequently produce a lower recovery than a cooperative sale would. There is almost always more time to act than borrowers initially assume.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Does the bank have to sell for market value?</h2>
      <p>The lender is not required to achieve the highest possible price, but they are required to take reasonable care to obtain a fair market value. This is an important distinction. In practice, mortgagee sales often achieve results below what a voluntary sale would achieve on the open market. There are several reasons for this: the property may be poorly maintained if the borrower has been in financial difficulty for some time, the marketing campaign is often shorter and narrower than a standard campaign, and the selling agent works for the lender, not the borrower.</p>

      <p>A compressed timeline also reduces competition among buyers. One of the most reliable drivers of strong sale prices is multiple genuine buyers competing for a property at the same time. A shortened or restricted campaign makes this harder to achieve. The result is that mortgagee sales typically produce outcomes that leave the borrower with less than they could have recovered, and sometimes with a shortfall rather than a surplus.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What does the borrower actually receive?</h2>
      <p>After the lender sells the property, the proceeds are applied in a specific order: sale costs first, then the outstanding loan balance including interest and any penalty charges. If there is money left after all of this is paid, that surplus belongs to the borrower. If the sale price is less than the total amount owed, including costs, the borrower faces a shortfall. That shortfall is not extinguished by the sale. The borrower remains personally liable for it, and the lender can pursue them for the difference through the courts.</p>

      <p>This is one of the least understood aspects of a mortgagee sale. Borrowers sometimes assume that once the property is sold, the debt is settled. That is only true if the sale price covers everything owed. Where it does not, the financial exposure continues after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Options available before a mortgagee sale occurs</h2>
      <p>The most important thing to understand is that once you receive a default notice, you have not yet lost the ability to influence the outcome. Several options are still available, and they typically produce better results than waiting for the lender to act.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Negotiate with the lender directly.</strong> Most lenders have hardship teams and are required under the National Credit Code to consider genuine hardship applications. A formal hardship variation can suspend or reduce repayments while you stabilise your situation. Lenders generally prefer this outcome to a forced sale, and many will agree to arrangements that give you time to resolve the position voluntarily.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Sell the property voluntarily before the lender acts.</strong> This is often the best financial outcome available to a borrower who cannot sustain the mortgage. A voluntary sale, conducted through a properly run campaign with competitive buyer interest, almost always achieves a better price than a mortgagee sale. You retain control of the timeline, the marketing approach, the choice of agent, and the negotiation. Any surplus after paying out the loan and sale costs comes to you rather than being absorbed in the bank's process. If you are considering this path, moving quickly matters because the lender's rights do not pause while you decide.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Seek legal and financial advice immediately.</strong> If you have been served with a default notice or are approaching a point where you cannot meet repayments, speak to a solicitor and a financial counsellor before the situation escalates. The National Debt Helpline (1800 007 007) provides free financial counselling. A solicitor can advise on the specific rights and timelines that apply to your mortgage documents and the Queensland legislation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do if they are in financial difficulty</h2>
      <p>Contact the lender early. The longer a default continues without communication, the fewer options remain. Lenders are required by law to refer borrowers to financial hardship assistance, but they need to be engaged to do so. Silence tends to accelerate the enforcement process, not slow it.</p>

      <p>Understand your hardship provisions under the National Credit Code. If your loan is regulated under the Code, you have a right to apply for a hardship variation and the lender must consider it properly. This applies to most standard residential mortgages in Queensland.</p>

      <p>If a voluntary sale is your best path forward, get an honest appraisal of the property's likely sale price before you commit to a timeline. Knowing whether the sale will clear the debt, and by how much, shapes every decision that follows. An agent who has transacted in your suburb recently can give you a realistic read on where comparable properties are selling and how long a campaign is likely to take.</p>

